                <m>9y^2+18y-3(3y-9)+9 = 0</m> with solutions <m>y=-2</m> and <m>y=1</m>.
                The corresponding critical points are <m>(3,-2)</m> and <m>(12,1)</m>.
                We use the Second Derivative Test to classify these critical points.
                Here we have
                <me>
                  g_{xx}(x,y) = 1, \ g_{yy}(x,y) = 18y+18, \ \text{ and }  \ g_{xy}(x,y) = -3
                </me>.
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Since <m>g_{xx}(3,-2)g_{yy}(3,-2) - g_{xy}(3,-2)^2 = -27 \lt 0</m>,
                      the function <m>g</m> has a saddle point at <m>(3,-2)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Since <m>g_{xx}(12,1)g_{yy}(12,1) - g_{xy}(12,1)^2 = 27 \gt 0</m> and <m>g_{xx}(12,1) \gt 0</m>,
                      the function <m>g</m> has a relative minimum at <m>(12,1)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For this function we have 
                <me>
                  f_x(x,y) = -2xye^{-x^2-2y^2}
                </me>
                and  
                <me>
                  f_y(x,y) = e^{-x^2-2y^2}-4y^2e^{-x^2-2y^2} = e^{-x^2-2y^2}(1-4y^2)
                </me>.
                Since <m>e^{-x^2-2y^2}</m> is never 0, the only way both <m>f_x(x,y)=0</m> and
                <m>f_y(x,y) = 0</m> is if <m>-2xy=0</m> and <m>1-4y^2=0</m>.
                This makes <m>y = \pm \frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>x=0</m>,
                giving us two critical points
                <m>\left(0, -\frac{1}{2}\right)</m> and <m>\left(0, \frac{1}{2}\right)</m>.
                We use the Second Derivative Test with
                <me>
                  f_{xx}(x,y) = 4x^2ye^{-x^2-2y^2} - 2ye^{-x^2-2y^2}
                </me>,
                <me> 
                  f_{yy}(x,y) = -12ye^{-x^2-2y^2}+16y^3e^{-x^2-2y^2}
                </me>,
                 and
                <me>
                  f_{xy}(x,y) = -2xe^{-x^2-2y^2}+8y^2xe^{-x^2-2*y^2}
                </me>
                to classify these critical points.
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Since <m>f_{xx}\left(0,-\frac{1}{2}\right)f_{yy}\left(0,-\frac{1}{2}\right) - f_{xy}\left(0,-\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 = 4\left(e^{-1/2}\right)^2 \gt 0</m> and <m>f_{xx}\left(0,-\frac{1}{2}\right) = e^{-1/2}</m>,
                      the function <m>g</m> has a relative minimum at <m>\left(0,-\frac{1}{2}\right)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Since <m>f_{xx}\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)f_{yy}\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right) - f_{xy}\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 = 4\left(e^{-1/2}\right)^2 \gt 0</m> and <m>f_{xx}\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right) = -e^{-1/2} \lt 0</m>,
                      the function <m>g</m> has a relative maximum at <m>\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                First we find the critical points of <m>f</m> on the triangular domain.
                The first order partial derivatives of <m>f</m> are
                <me>
                  f_x(x,y) = 2-2x \ \text{ and }  \ f_y(x,y) = 2 - 2y
                </me>.
                So <m>f_x(x,y) = 0</m> and
                <m>f_y(x,y) = 0</m> when <m>x=1</m> and <m>y=1</m>,
                giving us a single critical point <m>(1,1)</m>.
                This point is in the first quadrant and satisfies
                <m>y \lt  9-x</m>, so is in our domain.
                Next we check the boundaries <m>x=0</m> for <m>0 \leq y \leq 9</m>,
                <m>y=0</m> for <m>0 \leq y \leq 9</m>,
                and <m>y=9-x</m> for <m>0 \leq x \leq 9</m>.
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      When <m>x=0</m> we have <m>f(0,y) = 2+2y-y^2</m>.
                      Since <m>f'(y) = 2-2y</m>,
                      the only critical point of <m>f</m> is <m>(0,1)</m>.
                      The endpoints of this portion of the boundary are <m>(0,0)</m>,
                      and <m>(0,9)</m>, which we also need to check.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      When <m>y=0</m> we have <m>f(x,0) = 2+2x-x^2</m>.
                      Since <m>f'(x) = 2-2x</m>,
                      the only critical point of <m>f</m> is <m>(1,0)</m>.
                      The endpoints of this portion of the boundary are <m>(0,0)</m>,
                      and <m>(9,0)</m>, which we also need to check.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      When <m>y=9-x</m> we have <m>f(x,9-x) = 2+2x+2(9-x)-x^2-(9-x)^2</m>.
                      Since <m>f'(x) = -2x+2(9-x) = -4x+18</m>,
                      the only critical point of <m>f</m> is
                      <m>(4.5,4.5)</m> The endpoints of this portion of the boundary are <m>(0,0)</m>,
                      and <m>(0,9)</m>, which we also need to check.
